title: background_task_wait silently caps timeout_seconds at 110s with no LLM feedback
---
## Summary
background_task_wait accepts a timeout_seconds parameter but silently clamps it to max_wait_seconds (110.0) without informing the caller.

## Observed in daemon.log
LLM invokes: background_task_wait args={"id":48,"timeout_seconds":180}
Tool waits only 110s (max_wait_seconds), returns Timeout result.
LLM has no way to know its requested 180s was silently ignored — it may mis-schedule retries or misjudge elapsed time.

## Root Cause
src/background_task.ml line 1645-1646:
  let timeout_seconds = Float.min (Float.max raw_timeout 0.0) max_wait_seconds

max_wait_seconds = 110.0 (line 511). The cap is applied silently.

## Fix Options
1. Include the actual timeout used (and the cap) in the tool result when clamping occurs.
2. Document the maximum in the tool schema description so the LLM knows not to request more.
3. Both: add schema note + surface effective_timeout_seconds in the result.

## Severity
Medium — causes LLM confusion about elapsed wait time, leads to unnecessary re-calls.